Question 1

a)

Download the latest US State-level COVID-19 dataset from the New York Times data portal from https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-states.csv. You should be able to use read_csv() to immediately download this data as long as you are connected to the internet.

covid_raw <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-states.csv")

b)

Calculate and report in a sentence the mean number of new COVID deaths reported in New York from January 1st, 2022 to now. In order to do this:

  1. First filter the COVID State dataset to contain only information from New York
  2. Next, arrange the observations according to date.
  3. Create a new variable called new_deaths by using mutate(new_deaths = deaths - lag(deaths)). The lag() function will look backward one observation to obtain cases from the previous day.
  4. Filter the data frame to only include dates from 01/01/22 onwards. This column should be in date format, so using >= logic will work.
ny_covid21 <- covid_raw %>%
  filter(state == "New York") %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(new_deaths = deaths - lag(deaths)) %>%
  filter(date >= "2022-01-01")

mean_nd <- ny_covid21 %>%
  pull(new_deaths) %>%
  mean()

Answer:

The mean number of daily new COVID-19 deaths reported in New York since 01/01/2022 is 84.86.

c)

Compute and report the 95% confidence interval of the mean number of new deaths reported (using the standard formula for SE) in New York over from 01/01/22 onward.

standard_ci <- ny_covid21 %>%
  summarize(mean_nd = mean(new_deaths),
            total_n = n(),
            se = sd(new_deaths)/sqrt(total_n),
            lower_ci = mean_nd - 1.96*se,
            upper_ci = mean_nd + 1.96*se) %>%
  mutate(pretty_ci = str_c(round(mean_nd,2), " (", round(lower_ci,2), ", ", round(upper_ci,2), ")"))

ci_out <- standard_ci %>%
  pull(pretty_ci)

Answer:

The mean and 95% confidence interval for number of new deaths reported in New York from 01/01/21 onward is 84.86 (68.22, 101.5).

d)

Now compute and report the the 95% confidence interval of the mean number of new deaths reported (using bootstrapping to obtain the empirical 95% confidence interval) in New York over from 01/01/22 onward. Use 2000 bootstrap replicates to construct your confidence interval, and include a histogram of the distribution of bootstrapped mean reported deaths.

get_mean <- function(df){
  mean <- df %>%
    pull(new_deaths) %>%
    mean()
  return(mean)
}

create_bootstrap <- function(df){
  boot <- df %>%
    slice_sample(prop = 1, replace = TRUE)
  return(boot)
}

mean_bootstrap <- function(df){
  boot_m <- create_bootstrap(df) %>%
    get_mean()
  return(boot_m)
}

boot_res <- map_dbl(1:2000, function(x) mean_bootstrap(ny_covid21))

res_tibble <- tibble(run = 1:2000, mean = boot_res)

ggplot(data = res_tibble) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = mean), color = "white", fill = "blue") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Bootstrapped Distribution")

boot_ci <- res_tibble %>%
  summarize(lower_ci = quantile(mean, 0.025),
         upper_ci = quantile(mean, 0.975))

Answer:

The bootstrapped 95% CI for number of new deaths reported in New York from 01/01/22 onward is 68.41, 101.34.

e)

Compare the confidence intervals in parts (c) and (d). Are they the same? Different? If they are different, which confidence interval is wider, and by how much?

Answer:

The confidence intervals are almost identical in this case!

You have received two raw datasets containing the exposure status and demographics for a small pilot study. The data is currently a bit messy, so your first goal is to clean it and produce a small table 1 describing the demographics between two groups.

a)

Load the pilot_exposure.csv and pilot_demo.csv files into your environment. Figure out how to join them together so only participants with exposure information are included in the final file.

pilot_exp <- read_csv("data/pilot_exposure.csv")

exp_cleaned <- pilot_exp %>%
  mutate(id_number = str_remove(id_number, "STUDY-114:ID:") %>% as.numeric())

pilot_demo <- read_csv("data/pilot_demo.csv")

pilot_joined <- exp_cleaned %>%
  left_join(pilot_demo, by = "id_number")

b)

You have been asked to clean up the demographic data and code variables into the following categories:

Gender Male and Female (Current coding has 0 = Male and 1 = Female)

Ethnicity Hispanic and Non-Hispanic

Race White, Black, Unknown

Marital Status Single/Separated/Divorced and Married

Use string manipulation functions to create these variables and categories.

pilot_cleaned <- pilot_joined %>%

Question 3

Last week you explored associations between skeletal/girth measures and obesity status. For this problem, well be returning to those models using the same body_measures.csv dataset.

a)

If you did not complete Q3 in HW08: you must fit logistic regression models to explore the relationship between obesity status and three skeletal/girth measurements of your choice. This means you need to calculate BMI and create the 0/1 obesity outcome based on a BMI >= 30. You should result in 3 models, each one exploring the relationship between a measurement and obesity status. Your models can include adjustment for other variables if you wish.

If you completed Q3 in HW08: you can cut/paste your code from that assignment to set up the data and re-fit your three obesity status models.

bm_raw <- read_csv("data/body_measures.csv")

bm_bmi <- bm_raw %>%
  mutate(bmi = round(weight/(height/100)^2,1)) %>%
  mutate(obese = if_else(bmi >= 30, 1, 0))

wristg_obese_mod <- glm(obese ~ wrist_girth + age + gender, family = "binomial",
                       data = bm_bmi)

shoulderg_obese_mod <- glm(obese ~ shoulder_girth + age + gender, family = "binomial",
                       data = bm_bmi)

elbow_obese_mod <- glm(obese ~ elbow_diameter + age + gender, family = "binomial",
                       data = bm_bmi)

b)

One of your collaborators is very enthusiastic about reporting the BIC for each logistic regression model. This is a measure of overall model fit, with lower BIC indicating better fit. Use the broom package to access the BIC measure for each of your 3 logistic regression models and report them in a sentence using in-line coding.

wristmod_bic <- wristg_obese_mod %>%
  glance() %>%
  pull(BIC)

shouldermod_bic <- shoulderg_obese_mod %>%
  glance() %>%
  pull(BIC)

elbowmod_bic <- elbow_obese_mod %>%
  glance() %>%
  pull(BIC)

Answer:

The BIC for the wrist girth model is 169.087; the BIC for the shoulder girth model is 143.194; and the BIC for the elbow diameter model is 173.638.

c)

Excited by the prospect of comparing models based on BIC, your colleague asks you to calculate the 95% CI for the BIC of each model. Unfortunately, you cant find a formula anywhere online to do this so you decide to bootstrap them using 1000 replicates. Show the simulated bootstrap distribution of BIC values for each model, and report the empirical 95% confidence interval for each model.

get_BIC <- function(df, formula){
  f <- as.formula(formula)
  mod <- glm(f, family = "binomial",
                       data = df)
  BIC <- mod %>%
    glance() %>%
    pull(BIC)
  return(BIC)
}

get_bootstrap <- function(df){
  boot <- df %>%
    slice_sample(prop = 1, replace = TRUE)
  return(boot)
}

get_boot_BIC <- function(df, formula){
  boot_BIC <- get_bootstrap(df) %>%
    get_BIC(formula)
  return(boot_BIC)
}

wrist_boot_bic <- map_dbl(1:1000, function(x) get_boot_BIC(bm_bmi, "obese ~ wrist_girth + age + gender"))

shoulder_boot_bic <- map_dbl(1:1000, function(x) get_boot_BIC(bm_bmi, "obese ~ shoulder_girth + age + gender"))

elbow_boot_bic <- map_dbl(1:1000, function(x) get_boot_BIC(bm_bmi, "obese ~ elbow_diameter + age + gender"))

boot_tibble <- tibble(wrist = wrist_boot_bic, shoulder = shoulder_boot_bic,
                      elbow = elbow_boot_bic)

ggplot(boot_tibble) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = wrist), color = "white", fill = "blue") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "BIC")

ggplot(boot_tibble) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = shoulder), color = "white", fill = "red") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "BIC")

ggplot(boot_tibble) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = elbow), color = "white", fill = "purple") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "BIC")

longer_boot <- boot_tibble %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = any_of(c("wrist", "elbow", "shoulder")),
               names_to = "measure",
               values_to = "boot_mean")

booted_cis <- longer_boot %>%
  group_by(measure) %>%
  summarize(lower_ci = quantile(boot_mean, 0.025),
            upper_ci = quantile(boot_mean, 0.975),
            pretty_ci = str_c("(", round(lower_ci,2), ", ", 
                                 round(upper_ci, 2), ")"))

Answer:

The empirical bootstrap 95% confidence interval for BIC in the wrist model is (115.98, 212.21), for the shoulder model is (94.82, 182.73), and for the elbow model is (120.04, 223.19).

d)

Next up, youve been asked to produce a combined plot of the ORs and 95% CI for your measurements of interest and the BIC and bootstrapped 95% CI for each model in a forest plot type layout.

To do this: (1) Create one plot of the ORs and 95% CI for your three measurements association with obesity. (2) Create a second plot of the BICs and 95% CI for your three models. (3) Combine the two plots using patchwork.

Make sure that: (1) Your two sub-plots have consistent themes. (2) Your axes are properly labeled, and the variables and models have clear descriptions (not raw variable names). (3) You indicate somehow that the 95% CI for BIC has been bootstrapped.

or_data <- bind_rows(tidy(wristg_obese_mod, exponentiate = TRUE, conf.int = TRUE),
                     tidy(shoulderg_obese_mod, exponentiate = TRUE, conf.int = TRUE),
                     tidy(elbow_obese_mod, exponentiate = TRUE, conf.int = TRUE)) %>%

  mutate(term = str_replace(term, "_", " ") %>% str_to_title())

or_graph <- ggplot(data = or_data) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(y = term, x = estimate, xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 1), linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Odds Ratio", y = "Exposure of Interest", title = "Estimated Odds Ratios and 95% CI")

bic_lookup <- tibble(measure = c("wrist", "shoulder", "elbow"), bic = c(wristmod_bic, shouldermod_bic,
                                                                        elbowmod_bic))


bic_graph_dat <- booted_cis %>%
  left_join(bic_lookup, by = "measure") %>%
  mutate(measure = str_c(str_to_title(measure), " Model"))

bic_graph <- ggplot(bic_graph_dat) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(y = measure, x = bic, xmin = lower_ci, xmax = upper_ci)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(x = "BIC", y = "Model", title = "Model BICs with Bootstrapped 95% CI")


or_graph / bic_graph

Based on the 95% CIs in your graph in (e), would you say that the BIC for your three models differ? Why or why not?

Answer:

Although it isnt a definitive hypothesis test, it looks like the 95% confidence intervals for all three of these model BICs overlap, so I dont see evidence of a significant difference in fit between them.
